<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Hags Guide to the Major Convention<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.80)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=5246'>Cortney "dope5tar" Haggerty</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=5246&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 6, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> well, its been a while since i wrote an article, so to pass time at work, ive decided to give you guys another one.  enjoy!<br>
<br>
ok everyone, i know this is a bit late (being written at the tail end of convention season and all), but there are still a couple of cons this year to go, ala gen con, dragon con, Dcon, tacticon, freedomcon (maybe?), etc, plus this info should hold true for next years con run.  the point of this whole thing is to help the average gamer prepare for the awesome experience of the gaming convention.  there will be 3 main sections, tackled in order:<br>
<br>
1. Pre Convention Stuff<br>
<br>
2. During the Con<br>
<br>
3. Post Con Hoo Hah<br>
<br>
so, without further adieu, the article.<br>
<br>
<br>
in my opinion, everyone should attend a convention at least once.  the experience is great, you will meet a lot of cool people, see a lot of cool things, and generally have a blast of a weekend.  here is Hags comprehensive guide to the major convention.<br>
<br>
Part 1: Pre Con Stuff.<br>
<br>
the first part of attending a convention is PLANNING AHEAD.  i cant express this enough.  when you get wind of a convention that you and your buddies may be able to attend, start planning then.  get a list of people who want to/can go, and give them all a task.  for example, have john set up the hotel accomadations,  have jane set up plane tickets/ car situation, etc.  dont leave this to the last minute, as there will be several negative effects-  plane tickets will cost a fortune, the only available rooms at hotels will either be $500 a nite penthouse suites or homicide scene motels 20 miles away from the convention center.  you get the idea.<br>
<br>
next is PROFICIENT PACKING. make a list of things that you will need before the last second.  this includes, but is not limited to, toiletries,  CLEAN clothes, cameras, cards you may or may not use, a cooler with food/drinks, a book to read if you get bored, CDs, headphones, the kitchen sink, etc.  now this is important-  cut out about half of what you have written down.  think of it as cutting cards in a SW/LOTR deck.  many of the things you think you will need you wont, and besides, most likely you wont have space for half the junk anyways.  you most likely wont need it.  dont worry though,  you will regret cutting half the things you did and not cutting the crap you didnt.  its just the way it is. <br>
<br>
PLAYTEST!  very important.  try and come up with something clever that works.  if you cant come up with something yourself, or are just too dang lazy, jump on the internet and steal some decks from someone else.  whichever you do, be sure to play as many games with it as you can.  you need to be proficient with your deck.  you should be able to fill out the decklist from memory.  on a related note, be sure that you are aware of all the recent rulings/errata.  just imagine how unsatisfied you will be when you find out that your we must go warily/shards/gift of boats/deft in their movements deck isnt quite the broken machine that you thought it was after game 1.  also, try and find out what the locals of the convention area are playing.  most of your early competition will be from the horde of locals that come out.  you may be teched out against the mirror/STS/white arrows jank, but when johnny with his 96 card moria/weed deck kicks your can, you will wish you dmailed somebody.<br>
<br>
the next point is fairly important as well...GET MONEY.  conventions are not cheap.  at all.  a weekend pass will ususally run you at least $60, plus any tournament you want to enter will most likely charge an entry fee.  dont forget that, just like at football games, that hot dog that would cost you 90 cents at the sev will now cost you at least $5, most likely more like $8-9.  there is also the problem that the convention hall itself will try to lure you into spending money on all sorts of neat (mostly useless) things.  knives, movies, toys, oversize LOTR cards, deeply discounted SW cards, etc. will all cost you money.  mow lawns.  deliver papers. hell, maybe even get a job.  at any rate, you will need some flow to make the weekend enjoyable.<br>
<br>
USE YOUR CONTACTS.  you may know some people that will be attending, either from earlier cons/events, or non gamer friends/family members in the area.  they can help you navigate the area, find good places to eat, fill you in on the local meta, etc.  if you dont have any contacts, dont despair- youre not a loser (unless you have been to events prior and still have no contacts).  by the time you leave, you will meet people who you can add to your contact list for the next time.<br>
<br>
the last part of pre con poop is TALKING SMACK.   a little trash talk never hurt anyone.  if you do it right, people will give you some respect and maybe even find you cool enough to add to their contact list.  dont go overboard though...no one likes a d!ck.   oh, and dont tell people you are gonna kick their asses if you cant back it up.  its not real condusive to makin friends.<br>
<br>
2. During the Con.<br>
<br>
GET SOME SLEEP.  while we all have had the wonder tournament where after 2 hours of sleep you went 5-0 and gained a zillion rating points, today will not be a repeat of that day.  get at least a couple of hours.  i recommend getting some sort of sleeping pill, ambien is my personal choice, but dont do anything illegal.  the police will probably not let you out of the klink to play a card game.  just get some rest.<br>
<br>
so now youve made it to the convention center.  after you dink around in the main hall, see about 15 stormtroopers, 3 boba fetts, 1 death star gunner, a fat Vampirella and a 12 year old Dr Doom,  you head up to the room to play in the BIG EVENT.  <br>
<br>
PLAY GOOD DECKS. this may seem obvious, but how many times have you changed your deck at the last second, thinking &quot;man, this shimmer is unbeatable...how come i didnt think of this before?!?&quot;  usually this type of thinking comes from ignoring the first point of During the Con.  not to say that sometimes a deck change is necessary- see lollis origins day 2 deck as an example.  just use your head.  adding 2 weight of a legacy and 2 orc ambushers is never a good plan.  ever.<br>
<br>
now just because there may be big phat cash prizes on the line, dont go thinking youre gonna make it to day 2 just cuz youre good.  you need to play ONE GAME AT A TIME.  take a lesson from Rounders...dont let the vision of vegas blind you at KGBs table.  just because your opponent is a little kid doesnt mean he cant lay the smackdown on your legolas with 2 moria pumpers.  be aware of all the possiblities during the game, and take your time.  you have 45 minutes, usually sufficient.  dont be afraid to use them.<br>
<br>
in the same vein, be aware of all your cards as well as the opponents.  be sure to enforce your cards, ie. dont forget to make them discard 3 cards or add a burden with DDOTR.  also, and some will disagree with me on this, dont automatically do anything unless your opponent makes you.  its their job to remember their UTWE, not yours.  if you move and they start playing their shadow stuff, too bad, so sad.  its part of being a good tournament player.  remember your stuff.  very important.<br>
<br>
next point is to EAT. if youre starving, you wont be able to concentrate as well.  dont go out and eat a thanksgiving dinner though,   as it is highly improbable that there will be a detroit lions game on that you can nap through.  just eat something.  youll thank yourself day 2 if you do.<br>
<br>
similarly, DRINK.  if youre underage, drink water.  if youre 21+, drink water.  also, after the BIG EVENT, if youre 21+, go drink some alcohol.  it is good to unwind, tell some funny stories to your pals, meet some people, have some fun.  besides, it will help you sleep (see above point).  however, just like with eating, dont overdo it.  you will be sorry the next day, and your play will suffer.  while it makes for great TRs, i have yet to see an open champ with a hangover.  if youre underage, the same rules apply, with a couple extra...dont get caught, and dont tell them who bought you the shimmer.<br>
<br>
if you want to play competitively,  use this time to MAKE CONTACTS.  lets face it....everyone there has at least one thing in common- everyone plays LOTR.  make some friends.  youll be glad you did.<br>
<br>
TAKE NOTES/PICTURES. if you want to write TRs and have some great memories, do this.  nuff said.<br>
<br>
3. Post Con Hoo Hah.<br>
<br>
now that you have returned from the convention with a ton of useless junk, an empty wallet, an angry girlfriend, a crick in your neck and hopefully some phat prizes from your BIG EVENT domination,  you will want to share the experience with the community.  be sure to WRITE A TOURNAMENT REPORT.  everyone loves these things.  dont forget to include a pre event section, a tournament section, a post event section, and props and slops.  post some of the pictures you took on your web/member page so that people can put names to faces (and make fun of how you look). <br>
<br>
use this time to talk around and try to SET UP ANOTHER SUCCESSFUL CONVENTION TRIP.  after all, you had such a blast at the last one, why stop there?  see if you can find someones house to crash at for the next one (use the CONTACTS you made during the con).  wash, rinse, repeat baby.<br>
<br>
now, if applicable, TALK SOME MORE SMACK. if you won the whole thing,  you can now talk a lot of shimmer.  be sure to talk up your deck as &quot;(your states name here) secret tech&quot;.  feel free to expound upon current friendly rivalries.  now if you talked a lot of smack prior to the event, you can say &quot;told ya so&quot;,  or you can be silent and everyone will regard you with awe (or just consider you hella lucky).  however, if you talked mad smack prior to the event and utterly scrubbed out, you can either A) talk even more smack-  you dont want people to attack you when youre down, might as well strike first; or B) you can shut the frimbazel up since you obviously sucked it up at the BIG EVENT.  either is appropriate, its all a matter of your personal style.<br>
<br>
at any rate, be sure to attend as many of these as you can.  it will be one of the most fun, memorable experiences of your life.  i still remember my first trip to GenCon way back in &#39;94....senior trip, running out of gas in the middle of nowhere, hooking up with a hot chick dressed as a witch, getting all my mishras factories signed, losing my favorite hat,  laughing at people for trying to sell black lotuses for $30, etc.  i personally guarantee you will have an equally fun time.  hope you enjoyed this, be sure to give it a 5.<br>
<br>
see you at the con,<br>
<br>
hag<br>
<br>
